segments.text: We had another young man in his band named Boyd Rabin.
And actually, the dance was over.
One of the other band members, his girlfriend was going riding around.
And Rabin went along, and I went along.
He said he had David with the band.
What was he like?
Describe him.
He was a young man, probably early 30s.
He had a good band, but you didn't hear much of it.
He hadn't gotten up to the top yet.
Did Glenn Miller come here during your time?
I believe he was here one time.
But we had very good bands coming here.
But not often, because mainly the people who wanted to get
What were the biggest dances on the campus that y'all did?
Did y'all do the cotton ball?
what about ring dances or boot the during during this time who was the president gilchrist yet or was he dean bolton the president
Bear tracks both of them?
I didn't know that.
He had big feet.
Did you all see the president much?
No.
I don't think he attended.
When you and your buddies wanted to have a good time, where did you go and what did you all do?
We went out to Edmond.
Thank you.
Describe his place.
Well, there was a frame building.
But the main attraction was the bar.
You'd get off campus in order to drink beer.
You didn't have much money to drink beer, but we'd go out there and have it fraternized.
It's the guy that we had to walk from the campus down the edge, and it was right away.
What was the favorite brand of beer that you all drank?
Grand Prize, Southern Select?
Grand Prize, and what was that other one?
Southern Select?
Yeah, that was one of them.
I had forgotten that name, but it was Budweiser.
Oh, sure.
Yeah, but some of the beers were cheaper than others, were they not?
You probably drank the cheap beers.
I don't recall ever getting bruised off out there.
They just went out there just for the company, you know.
And most people walked.
Right.
Did you and your buddies ever go out to the clay pits swimming?
I didn't go out there, but I know there's a lot of guys that did go out there to the clay pits.
Was there a bootlegger anywhere around that anybody knew about?
I don't remember one.
Did any of the guys in the project house ever have beer or whiskey in their room?
No.
No, there was a clean place.
We didn't bring anything in there.
Was it okay to smoke in the room?
It seemed like I don't ever remember having to go outside to smoke.
I don't know.
I know there was maybe one or two guys in my room that smoked.
Where did y'all go for a movie?
Oh, at the campus.
DeGuyen Hall?
DeGuyen Hall?
No, not very often.
I don't recall that they had movies.
Oh, I'm sorry.
You mean the campus theater?
Yeah.
Yes, yes.
Yeah.
They're not doing movies.
They're doing country music.
That's a big thing nowadays.
That's where we used to go to see a movie.
Do you remember where you were on December 7, 1941?
Yes.
Please describe that.
That was Sunday.
And we didn't go to church that day.
We were just lounging around in the rooms and everything.
Some guys had this radio on and there was great excitement about the bombing of Pearl Harbor.
I was listening to that thing and I went down the hall and I said, well, we're into it now.
And I knew then that we were involved in a big war.
And I'm sure we all were pretty silent and listening to the news and being really scared, I guess you might say.
Although it wasn't frightening per se, but it was solemn, one of the solemn things.
We are now involved in it.
And then I said to these guys,
Well, we're into it now.
Because, you know, there's been a lot of, not a lot, but reluctance for the United States to get into this business.
But we didn't have any choice after that happened.
And so, I guess that kind of determined my future, you know, more or less.
People thought I was reneging
on military things because here I am, 30 years old, and wearing civilian clothes.
And that was one of the influences in putting me into service in 1942.
Now, did you volunteer?
Yes.
I volunteered, but I wanted to join the Navy.
I don't know why.
I just thought it was romantic, and I had some friends who were in the Navy.
But they weren't taking any volunteers.
So I really did the best thing not going into the Navy when I volunteered with the Air Force.
And they had no trouble taking me there.
Now, when did you sign up?
Do you remember?
October 1942.
October 1942.
So you had finished two full years.
Did you go here in the summer of 1942?
Yes, I did.
And I had signed up.
to go to the fall.
Things were in a turmoil.
Nothing was the same as it was before.
I mean, I didn't know whether the band would continue or not.
And people were, men were leaving by the door being either drafted or going for some reason other than maybe because of the military.
That's the kind of turmoil.
And you get involved in that kind of thing.
And you wonder why, well, what am I going to do about this thing?
And I'd say, well, how do you stand out of the service?
Well, that was one of the reasons why I volunteered.
Another reason was I just got picked up in it.
And I told my mother that I was volunteering.
She said, you were too old to go to the military.
I said, well.
And where did you go to enlist?
I went to Waco.
I can't pull up these boards.
I went up there and volunteered.
And they sent me up to Dallas.
They involved you.
They signed you up.
And you were sent back.
I was sent back to Waco.
I worked in a state in Dallas.
Not too many days.
I know there's a bunch of us here in Oregon.
And I ended up at Mineral Wells, one of the places out there.
And then they sent me back to Waco.
And I stayed in Waco, this was October when I went in, and I stayed in Waco until February.
And then I was enrolled in an Air Corps maintenance thing.
And they sent me to Nebraska, to the Nebraska Air Base up there for training as a mechanic.
And thence, from there I was shipped to California and assigned to a group in the 363rd Fighter Group.
From there I ended up in Europe.
These years are most impressive to me because I was involved in the thing.
involved in maintenance to a fighter.
What kind of fighters were in your squad?
And that was the big.
Mustangs.
Yeah, that was the big fighter thing in the big area.
They had the 47s and they had the 51s, and they both were fighter things.
But if anything, the 51 was probably a superior product because it had the speed of 750 miles an hour.
When the war started, you said things changed around here.
Describe how it changed.
How did attitudes change among the students?
Everybody was excited.
You know, and it felt like everything you did, you had to do in a hurry.
And you go here, and I had already signed up for classes.
And I'd gone to some classes, but I had to go to the...
When the war started, who did you and your friends think was going to win the war?
Do you remember anybody arguing against?
No.
It seemed like
You know, everybody was into the thing, and they went into it voluntarily, so to speak.
Well, everybody was really .
You know, the Japanese were doing something like that.
And so we .
Everybody, I don't remember anybody ever objecting to it.
Now, during that second, your sophomore year here, though,
when the war started, the Aggieland Orchestra is still going strong.
Did some of the members of the orchestra leave early?
I think some of them did, but I think I was the first one that they called.
But I'm sure that some of the other two were in the military out at A&M.
They probably called up.
Did you all change your repertoire when the war started?
Did you all play some different songs?
Well, some of them we did.
Some of those English songs.
White Cliffs of Dover.
That's the one I was trying to think of.
And the one about the Mockingbird Sands.
On Blueberry Hill.
No, but that was another one.
Blueberry Hill.
The Mockingbird Sands.
On some street.
And there was about four or five of those songs that were being popularized.
I'll be seeing you.
We lost contact with one strong in the United States.
During that second year here, did any of the faculty leave, faculty and staff?
I don't remember whether it was or not.
Of course, you know, you didn't know very many of the staff I was working with.
And I think I was probably one of the first ones to pay off, so I don't know who left that job.
They had that movie made here, you know, that stuff.
Was that while you were here?
No, it was after I left.
Oh, boy.
Oh, I was hoping that you would have recalled that.
I said it.
We've never been whipped, I think.
Never been licked.
Never been licked.
They said that really changed the campus.
Cables running here and there and all that stuff.
Now, you came back here then after the war.
Yes.
When did you get back?
I got out of service September of 1945.
And I didn't realize it, but I could come back to A&M.
I thought, well, I've got time on my hands.
I could count the year that, you know, the student year that I started.
So before I decided to leave the military, I was at home.
I told my mother, she was going to be 30 or something like that.
I thought I was going to stay in the military, stay in the Air Force.
She said, well, I hope you do.
college education.
And so I didn't know really what I wanted to do, but I went back and I said I couldn't get into school now, but I got out of the military just in time to get enrolled in the fall semester.
And how...
How had your attitude about college, how has it changed by the years?
Well, I guess not many of them.
The military gave you $69.
But were you more determined?
Well, I was more into it.
Oh yeah, I made better grades.
I was older.
What was your major?
What were you dreaming of doing with that degree?
Thank you.
Thank you.
And where did you live?
Did you play in the orchestra again?
Well, it's pretty much the same as something he made.
Before, the management of the Arc Park Center didn't have a steering director.
But they got a man named Bill Stringer.
I don't know if he's on that page on the campus.
He was either head or director of Agri.
And they didn't have a director.
Mr. Turner, was he a faculty member?
I think that he was.
San Luis, Texas, and San Marcos?
No, no, it's the one up at East Texas.
East Texas?
Yeah.
Yeah.
When was that?
After you left?
Yeah.
Mr. Turner here, did he conduct the Aggieland Orchestra?
Did the instrumentation change after the war?
The big band there was dying.
And the big band, you couldn't afford them.
And they just didn't get out and threw around like they used to do.
We didn't get to bring any of them down here.
Did you all get paid when you, were you still getting paid cash when you did play?
Yes, I was.
Do you remember what the pay was after the war?
No, I sure don't.
I didn't depend on that as much because I had the GI Bill.
But that didn't cut it either anymore because of the higher costs and everything.
Now, back before the war, did someone conduct the orchestra or did you all just play together?
We just played together.

and uh... after the war or most of the concerts uh... most y'all played mostly on-campus didn't travel marley or really how did you travel thing but there's more more read well the same as it was before things under different hospices her still an employee of the university
You said that you didn't read music much.
Do you remember any tune that was very difficult for you to...
to learn and one that was very easy.
What was the easiest or the hardest?
Well, the hardest one was .
Those were easy?
Yeah.
I think most of them are students who had not gotten involved.
Were they newcomers?
Some of them were.
Yes, they were.
I'd say that maybe 50% were new.
Who was your closest Aggieland Orchestra friend?
Well, I guess Murray Evans.
Murray Evans?
Yeah, the guitar.
He was the man that got me down here.
Of course, he was graduated, I think, well before I did.
And there was several of those guys.
Where was he from?
He was from McKinney.
Okay.
We were both from McKinney.
And then after the war, you were the oldest man in the group?
I'm sure.
Did they look to you for advice?
No.
They're pretty independent people.
All right.
After the war, how different was the behavior pattern of the students?
They did.
They did?
Because, you know, the enlisted man was not allowed to drink in the service.
You did not get any quota, you know, like the, where the aviators or other people with rank, you know, they were issued overseas, they were issued drinks.
And some of them, sometimes they would give their drinks, you know, some of them didn't drink, they'd give it to their people who were under them.
So some drinking in the service.
Of course, if you got off to London,
or Paris or someplace, you know.
Then you let your hair down, you know.
But back on the campus, there was no control, and you could buy all the whiskey you wanted, you could do anything.
Well, we didn't drink a lot.
I didn't drink a lot, but I drank.
You may not want to put this on, but there was a group of people in Bryan who were civilians
They'd bring drinks out there, and we'd all go out and sit under a tree and shoot the bull, you know, and have a few.
All right, now, was this beer or whiskey?
Mostly beer.
Beer.
Now, was Whiskey Bridge yet operating?
Drove out towards Snook just beyond the... Yeah.
Yeah, that's where the whiskey was bought.
You know, this was a dry county.
Right.
We used to go out on Friday, drive out and get a pint or a quart or something, you know, and we'd...
Now, so Uncle Ed's was there before the war, but there also after the war.
I don't remember ever going to Uncle Ed's after the war.
I remember, let me think about this.
Well, I believe it was still there because I was involved with a young lady from out of Waco.
And one time her parents brought her down for a dance or something.
And we would probably have another band in at the end, you know.
But anyway, I can remember she and I hitchhiked down to the edge one day.
So I'm sure he was still out there by that time.
On the south edge of the campus, the project houses were filled with veterans.
And were there lots of trailers there also?
I don't remember the trailers.
But, you know, they converted it, you know, to quarters for married students, you know.
So they lived in the project houses.
What did the married students' wives, what did they do?
Did they work around?
I think some of them did, but I don't recall anything in particular.
Of course, they kind of had their own cliques, you know, the married students did.
And we didn't fraternize, you know, with them very much, or know them, for that matter.
What did you and your buddies think about the Aggie band?
Oh, we loved it.
Of course, we had, nobody didn't have to, but, you know, we got a lot of members of the bands in the orchestra.
I see.
Several of the trumpet band, and I know that maybe it might have been, say, 60% of the Aggieland Orchestra were band members.
Of course, they had the advantage of being good musicians, you know, and they were, they were chosen.
from out of the band to play in the orchestra.
And let's see, every instrument y'all had except the piano, the band...
I don't think the band furnished them.
No, no, I mean, but those instruments, the people could play those instruments in the marching band.
Oh, yes.
Yeah, they got those guys from over there who probably maybe had had
orchestra experience somewhere in their civilian life.
When you came back from the war, describe going to an Aggie football game.
How did things change before the war and after the war?
I'm sorry to say, but I was not much of a football man.
So I don't know whether it would be any difference or not.
Of course, you know, the Corps has always supported athletic things, pretty much.
I was not in the Corps either time, so I guess I didn't get that, you know, I don't know what you call it.
As far as you were aware, what student officials
corps commander, band commander, whatever.
What student leaders had the highest prestige?
Well, of course, the military was pretty... Now, at one time, after I was graduated, I went to work in the military department over there keeping records.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
But they didn't pay.
Meantime, I had gotten married.
And I couldn't feed a wife on...
the records keeper's salary, so that's when I left A&M.
All right.
When did you start going steady with this future wife?
Was it while you were a student?
Yes.
How did you meet?
Oh, let's see.
We were downtown.
No, I guess the first time I met her, I was going to Caldwell on the bus, and she was going to Giddings on the bus, and that's when I met her.
And then I found out that she worked at the fiscal department.
At that time, she'd been working over there for a couple of years.
And I used to meet her at lunch, you know, at the cafe.
She'd come over to cafes on the north side for lunch.
What cafe?
Where would you all meet?
I don't remember the names of them, but they were right along in that.
right across from the post office there.
They changed the names, you know, and it'd be one name this time, the next time you went, somebody else owned it.
But we used to go over there, and I'd beat her over there, and we'd have lunch together.
When you went out on date, where did you go?
To the Boogamies.
There wasn't very much to do, you know, around here.
Campus or downtown?
Downtown.
She lived with her sister and brother-in-law down on East 29th Street.
Which was the best movie downtown?
The Palace.
And then, of course, they had the Queen.
And another, I don't remember what that other name was, but they were all owned by the same people.
The Shieldmans, I think.
Yes.
Yeah, Bill Shieldman.
Did you have a car by that time?
No, I didn't.
I didn't get a car until after I went into the insurance business.
Well, how did you all get around when you were seeing her?
Well, we had a bus.
Okay.
We had a bus to get into town.
Okay.
She'd either come out here and we'd louse around on the campus or else we'd, you know, various places, yak and, you know.
Did y'all go to dances?
Yes, uh-huh.
Occasionally, when sometime a big band had come into town.
Having been in the orchestra, sometimes I didn't have to pay.
Uh-huh.
Let's see.
One of the questions I should have asked earlier, when you were a student, did you attend any religious services here?
We used to go to church over at First Baptist Church in College State.
